            <fr:title text="Boolean valuations: conjunction">Boolean valuations: conjunction</fr:title>
          </fr:frontmatter>
          <fr:mainmatter>
            <html:p>         The same idea comes to the fore when we look at the remaining connectives in this language.
        In each case, we'll choose how to deal with them based on their intended interpretation: <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land ]]></fr:tex> as something like "and"; <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\lor ]]></fr:tex> as something like "or"; <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\rightarrow ]]></fr:tex> as something like "implies" or "if...then"; and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\bot ]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\top ]]></fr:tex> as, well, we'll get to them in a minute.
        We're working with a very simple and coarse-grained setup here, so the match might not be perfect.
        But thinking about how "and" and "or" and "if...then" work can get us some way along the path to seeing what we're doing with these connectives, just like thinking about "not" can help with understanding <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\neg ]]></fr:tex>.
        Here's how Boolean valuations deal with conjunctions: a conjunction <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \land  B]]></fr:tex> gets the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> on a given valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> exactly when <html:em>both</html:em> of its components <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[B]]></fr:tex> get value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex> on the valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex>.
        Otherwise, the conjunction <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[A \land  B]]></fr:tex> gets the value <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
</html:p>
            <html:p>         Why deal with conjunction this way?
        Think, for example, about the claim "The moon is made of green cheese, and Carl is a good dog".
        Is this claim true or false?
        Well, "the moon is made of green cheese" is false, and "Carl is a good dog" is true.
        So if someone said to us "the moon is made of green cheese and Carl is a good dog", then what they've said is false: the falsity of the first part undermines the whole claim.
        They in effect said that both of these were true, and that's not so; so what they've said is false.
        This is why, for <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\land ]]></fr:tex>, we go with a setup that requires both components to be true on a valuation for the conjunction itself to be true on that valuation.
        Just as with negation, we can record this information in a table:            
</html:p>
            <fr:tree show-metadata="false">
              <fr:frontmatter>
