</html:table>
              </fr:mainmatter>
            </fr:tree>
            <html:p>Since this table is for a binary connective rather than a unary one, we read it slightly differently from the table for negation.
Let's say you want to use this table to calculate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p \land  q)]]></fr:tex> on some valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w]]></fr:tex> where you know that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex> and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>.
        Use the left component of the conjunction to choose a row of the table, by finding the appropriate value along the left edge.
        In this case, the left component is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[p]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, so you choose the bottom row of the table.
        Then, use the right component of the conjunction to choose a column of the table, by finding the appropriate value along the top edge.
        In this case, the right component is <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[q]]></fr:tex>, and <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>, so you choose the column headed by <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[\mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>.
        By finding the entry where this row and column meet, you find the value your conjunction must take; in this case, this tells us that <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[w(p \land  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>.
        As with negation, you might find that you don't need the table for long, that it's enough to remember that both components must be true for the conjunction to be true.
        But as with negation, we're going to see more complex alternatives in a moment, so it's good to be able to read these tables.
</html:p>
            <html:p>         The value of a negation or a conjunction, in a Boolean valuation, depends only on the values of its component(s).
        This is so even when the components are themselves compound sentences.
        So, for example, consider a valuation <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v]]></fr:tex> where <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p) = v(q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>; you now know enough to calculate <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg (p \land  \neg  q))]]></fr:tex>.
        Do it step by step: first <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, then <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(p \land  \neg  q) = \mathsf {\mathbf {F}}]]></fr:tex>, and finally <fr:tex display="inline"><![CDATA[v(\neg (p \land  \neg  q)) = \mathsf {\mathbf {T}}]]></fr:tex>.
        So once you know the Boolean tables for each connective, you will be able to calculate the value of any formula on any Boolean valuation, no matter how complex the formula is, so long as you know the values of the atomic formulas it contains.
</html:p>
